<div class="loophead">
<h2 class="boxh3"><a href="http://www.castaliahouse.com/sensor-sweep-eerie-ray-bradbury-dd-gauntlet/" rel="bookmark" title="Sensor Sweep: Eerie, Ray Bradbury, D&#038;D Gauntlet" class="tre">Sensor Sweep: Eerie, Ray Bradbury, D&#038;D Gauntlet</a></h2>
<span class="postcalendar"><a href="http://www.castaliahouse.com/sensor-sweep-eerie-ray-bradbury-dd-gauntlet/" rel="bookmark" title="Sensor Sweep: Eerie, Ray Bradbury, D&#038;D Gauntlet" class="tre">Monday , 4, August  2025  </a></span>
<span class="postauthor">Morgan</span>
<span class="postcategory"><a href="http://www.castaliahouse.com/category/sensor-sweep/" rel="category tag">Sensor Sweep</a></span>
<span class="postcomment"><a href="http://www.castaliahouse.com/sensor-sweep-eerie-ray-bradbury-dd-gauntlet/#comments">3 Comments</a></span>
</div>
		<div class="entry clear">
        
          
                <p><b>Fiction </b>(<a href="https://www.blackgate.com/2025/07/25/the-fundamentals-of-sword-planet-part-v-charles-nuetzel/#comments">Black Gate</a>): I heard about Charles Nuetzel, who’d written some<img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-103359" src="http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/Charles-Nuetzel-Warriors-of-Noomas-small-min-152x256.jpg" alt="" width="152" height="256" srcset="http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/Charles-Nuetzel-Warriors-of-Noomas-small-min-152x256.jpg 152w, http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/Charles-Nuetzel-Warriors-of-Noomas-small-min.jpg 475w" sizes="(max-width: 152px) 100vw, 152px" /> Howard-like and Burroughs-like tales. I’d stumbled on his book called <em>Warriors of Noomas</em>. After a search on the net, I found an email address and sent one flying into the void. I wasn’t sure he was even alive, but he answered and we became frequent correspondents and friends. He too was a huge fan of Edgar Rice Burroughs and quite a bit of his writing was ERB inspired. He’d become a pulp writer and book packager for Powell Publications.</p>
<p><b><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-103360" src="http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/amazing_stories_194103-174x256.jpg" alt="" width="174" height="256" srcset="http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/amazing_stories_194103-174x256.jpg 174w, http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/amazing_stories_194103-160x235.jpg 160w, http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/amazing_stories_194103.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 174px) 100vw, 174px" />Edgar Rice Burroughs </b>(<a href="https://arkhaven.substack.com/p/the-city-of-mummies">Arkhaven Substack</a>): A few decades back, if you went to Waldenbooks or B. Dalton Bookseller at your local mall, the science fiction section would have a sizeable Edgar Rice Burroughs section. Ace Books had the Carson of Venus and Pellucidar series, and various stand alone novels generally with Frank Frazetta covers. Ballantine Books kept the Tarzan and John Carter/Mars/Barsoom series in print with Boris Vallejo and Neal Adams covers for Tarzan and Michael Whelan covers for John Carter of Mars series.</p>
<p><b>Tolkien</b> (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YHO8vclsvR4">Malcolm Guite</a>): <span style="color: #131313;">We look together at the evolution of one of the most beautiful poems in the Lord of the Rings</span></p>
<p><b>Robert E. Howard </b>(Sprague de Camp Fan): Glenn Lord’s <em>The Last Celt: A<img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-103361" src="http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/dark_valley_destiny-l-sprague-de-camp-173x256.jpg" alt="" width="173" height="256" srcset="http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/dark_valley_destiny-l-sprague-de-camp-173x256.jpg 173w, http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/dark_valley_destiny-l-sprague-de-camp-160x236.jpg 160w, http://www.castaliahouse.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/dark_valley_destiny-l-sprague-de-camp.jpg 250w" sizes="(max-width: 173px) 100vw, 173px" /> Bio-Bibliography of Robert Ervin Howard</em> (1976) is a foundational and unique contribution to Howard studies. Lord was not only a biographer but also the primary literary executor of Howard’s legacy for decades, and his work blends elements of biography, bibliography, archive, and homage. It is not a conventional biography, but its impact on every other work about Howard—including the bios by Finn, Vick, and Oliver—is profound. <a href="http://www.castaliahouse.com/sensor-sweep-eerie-ray-bradbury-dd-gauntlet/#more-103358" class="more-link">Read More</a></p>
  
         

